<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Phlox</i> <i>pulvinata</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous and subshrub layers with <i>Anelsonia</i> <i>eurycarpa</i>, <i>Astragalus</i> <i>kentrophyta</i>, <i>Astragalus</i> <i>purshii</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>suffruticosa</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>incanum</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>ovalifolium</i>, <i>Festuca</i> <i>brachyphylla</i>, <i>Ipomopsis</i> <i>congesta</i>, <i>Ivesia</i> <i>gordonii</i> and <i>Lupinus</i> <i>argenteus</i> var. <i>montigenus</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 40 cm; cover is open to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Phlox pulvinata</i> characteristically present in the herbaceous layer (NatureServe 2007).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Fell-fields on summits and ridges, snow beds, basins and slopes. Lag gravel covers the soil, and patterned ground features are present on summits and ridges. Substrates can be granitic and metamorphic including andesite or chalky rhyolite.  </div>
</div>

        
