<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Phlox pulvinata </i>is a compact, caespitose perennial herb growing to 10 cm tall. Plants have woody caudices with taproots and surface roots that represent a greater biomass than the aboveground biomass. Plants reproduce infrequently from seed when environmental conditions are favorable. Rhizomes and layering allow plants to expand (Billings 1974). Many botanical sources use the name <i>P. caespitosa </i>ssp<i>. pulvinata</i>. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance, first recognized in alpine fell-fields in the Medicine Bow Mountains of Wyoming, also occurs in Idaho (Caicco 1983), Nevada (NatureServe 2007a), and at the highest elevations of the Sierra Nevada and Sweetwater Mountains in California (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). The range of <i>P. pulvinata </i>overlaps that of <i>P. covillei </i>in the Californiaâ€™s mountains. The ecological differences between <i>P. condensata, P. covillei, </i>and <i>P. pulvinata </i>are not well known (see the <i>Phlox covillei </i>alliance). The plants of <i>P. covillei </i>are tightly cushion-like; those of <i>P. pulvinata </i>are not tightly cushion-like (Hickman 1993). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
